x4freetext: The target was composed of 323 microgramm/cm2 of 11-B
enriched boron, evaporated onto 100 mg/cm2 of Ta
backing.  The backing ensured complete stopping of the
beam in the target and was used both to monitor the
beam current and to reduce the large gamma-ray Doppler
broadening.  Scattering chamber was equipped with a
cold trap in order to avoid carbon build up on the
target.  At the end of the overall 100 hours run time
no carbon build-up on the target was observed.
For an accurate measurement of the integrated beam
cross-sections for the 301 keV Ta gamma-ray was
compared with the calculated values according to the
A 95 cm3 detector at an angle of 125 degree.
The detector was used to accumulate detailed low energy
A high-purity intrinsic Ge detector at 55 degree
with respect to the beam direction for the
accumulation of all gamma-rays up to 7MeV.
